The Gulf Cooperation Council has existed since 1981 and the six original member states are Saudi Arabia, UAE, Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman and Qatar. No nations have been added since the union's inception and no nation has withdrawn or been removed from the union, either. The US has significant military infrastructure in most of the member nations. Qatar went too far, according to Saudi Arabia and others, allowing Islamic extremist terrorist groups and ISIS to operate and be funded. I believe the Emir of Qatar will come to his senses and return to ruling with actions that create the best return on investment. Terrorism is bad for business.

Negotiations will likely continue and all sides will likely stall as long as possible. Primary GCC states will likely be hesitant to fully push Qatar out of GCC and Qatar will likely be hesitant to more fully accept security and economic support or guarantees from non-GCC states.

If the participants hold back emotions and act rationally this is not going to happen either before or after Jan 1, 2018. Reality politics will lead to an understanding which will prevent this step from being taken.

So far, it seems as though only the UAE is advancing the idea of Qatar leaving the GCC (https://www.forbes.com/sites/dominicdudley/2017/07/17/qatar-ejection-from-gcc/#76d0562752d7). This could become more realistic if the other three member states begin echoing that sentiment. But with tensions probably greatest between Qatar and UAE, it shouldn't come as a surprise this language is being used.
